${h2('Backgrounds')}
      
      <p>The Flexi system does not have a set skill list. Instead players buy
        character backgrounds which represent roles that a character has had
        in their life. If a character attempts a task which they have had some
        training, or experience, in as part of their background then it will
        enhance the roll. All backgrounds consists of two values. The first represents the number of
        dice that is added to the task resolution roll. The second is a set
        value which is added to the dice total.  For Example:-</p>
        
        <p><em>Thaddeus is attempting to grow wheat in a field.  The game master decides that
        the appropriate attribute is Judgement.  Luckily Thaddeus has a background in Farmhand.
        He takes his two JUDG dice (Thaddeus has very poor Judgement) and adds the three dice
        from his background in Farmhand).  After he's rolled he will get a total value which
        he can then add his experience in Farmhand to.</em></p>
        
        <p>A detailed description of the mechanics for backgrounds is presented in the Task
        resolution section of the rules.  For now players must understand two factors that define backgrounds, their rank and their type.</p>
        
        ${h3('Rank')}
        
        <p>Rank is a representation of the applicability of a background and determines the cost at
        character generation to buy it and the cost of experience to upgrade it. Some backgrounds can be used
        in far more situations than others, compare the background MI5 Agent to the background Thug.  The former
        has significant training in almost any situation you can care to imagine whereas the latter does not.  For example:-
        
        <P><em>Thaddeus has the background thug, whereas his close friend Reggie has the background MI5 agent. The GM agrees
        that they can both use their backgrounds to outpace a gang of goons that are chasing them.  The GM also agrees that
        they can both use their backgrounds to intimidate someone.  However when it comes to seduction only Reggie gets to
        use his background.  The GM has decided that Thug is not really a background that seduces high class women at high society
        events therefore Thaddeus has no experience at this and thus cannot use it.</em></p>
        
        <p>There is one benefit to having backgrounds which are not as applicable as others, they cost less.  A low rank background
        costs significantly less to buy at character generation, and to upgrade, compared to the higher ranking backgrounds.</p>
    
        <h2>Type</h2>
        
        <p>There are three types of background which determine when the background can be used.</p>
        
        ${h3('Vocations')}
        
        <p>Vocational backgrounds represent the skills, experiances and training that the characters
        have recieved during portions of their life. Any occupation, trade or profession could be considered a
        vocational background as long as the character could have picked up relevent experiances from it.
        Vocations are deliberately vague so that there is no constraint imposed by a set skill list. With specific skills it is too easy
        for a player, unfamiliar with a system, to neglect to buy an important skill for their character concept. There is also the
        fact that some players have to sacrifice important skills because the cost at character generation is too large.</p>
        
